SIMPLE: lithic
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lithic
<hw>Lith"ic</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧th"⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>liqiko`s</grk> of or belonging to stones, fr. <grk>li`qos</grk>
stone: cf. F. <ets>lithique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or
pertaining to stone; <as>as, <ex>lithic</ex>
architecture</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the formation of
uric-acid concretions (stone) in the bladder and other parts of the
body; <as>as, <ex>lithic</ex> diathesis</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lithic acid</b></col> <fld>(Old Med. Chem.)</fld>,
<cd>uric acid. See <cref>Uric acid</cref>, under
<er>Uric</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lithic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lithic
<hw>Lith"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A medicine which
tends to prevent stone in the bladder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lithic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lithic
<hw>Lith"ic</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Lithium</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to or denoting lithium or some of its
compounds.</def> <rj><au>Frankland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lithiophilite</ent>⟦br⟧
